    "name": {
      "name": "S-adenosyl-l-methionine hydroxide adenosyltransferase",
      "short": "SAM_OH_AdoTrfase"
    },
    "description": [
      {
        "text": "<p>The S-adenosyl-L-methionine (SAM) hydroxide adenosyltransferase family groups several fluorinase and chlorinase enzymes whose common feature is that they mediate nucleophilic reactions of their respective halide ions to the C-5' carbon of SAM [[cite:PUB00054078]]. These enzymes utilise a rigorously conserved amino acid side chain triad (Asp-Arg-His) which may have a role in activating water to hydroxide ion. Structural studies indicate that the protein is a homotrimer, with each monomer being composed of N- and C-terminal domains [[cite:PUB00030772], [cite:PUB00048880], [cite:PUB00151506]]. The N-terminal domain has a central seven-stranded \u03b2-sheet, which combines parallel and antiparallel strands sandwiched between \u03b1-helices. The C-terminal domain forms a \u03b2-barrel with a greek-key topology. SAM is bound at the interface between the C-terminal domain of one monomer and the N-terminal domain of the neighbouring monomer, with a total of three molecules bound by the trimer. This group of proteins, which are predominantly found in prokaryotes, used to be known as DUF62 [[cite:PUB00101218]].</p>",
        "llm": false,
        "checked": false,
        "updated": false
      }
    ],
